<BR><img src=http://webpost.net/wi/withroo/haru.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Character design</span><hr size=1> Answering your first question directly, I don't believe there is any &quot;set&quot; kind of poses for character design. Those angled headshots you described are typically used to get the facial features and any other attributes on the head sorted out from different viewpoints (for consistency, possibly?).<br>
<br>
As for full-bodied poses, it's already been said before me. Use poses that emphasize personality of the character; slouching for the lazy/laid-back, straight backed and arms akimbo for the proud and ambitious (stereotypically).<br>
<br>
&quot;Subtle&quot; personalities (the mysterious, the quiet, the dreamers, etc.) are a bit more of a pain to figure; for me, I have them doing something casual like sitting or staring off into the distance (or with eyes closed) with a faint smile.<br>
<br>
